            , his master.</p>
               <p>EDWARD MINISTER. I am a <rs id="t18310908-291-viclabel1497" type="occupation">tailor</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-291-victim2113 t18310908-291-viclabel1497"></join>. The prisoner was my <rs id="t18310908-291-deflabel1498" type="occupation">errand-boy</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-291-defend2111 t18310908-291-deflabel1498"></join> - I missed some claret cloth, and after his left me I found him in custody at the station-house in Vinestreet, and saw a piece of blue cloth there, which I compared with a pattern I had.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-291-person2114">
                  JOSHUA 
                  FREDERICK CLEMENTS
               <interp inst="t18310908-291-person2114" type="surname" value="FREDERICK CLEMENTS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-291-person2114" type="given" value="JOSHUA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-291-person2114" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an inspector of the Police. I received the prisoner in charge, on the 15th of July, and from information, I asked him what had become of the cloth, lost from his master's while he was in his service; he said voluntarily that if I went to No. 14. Crown-street, I should find a piece of blue cloth in a cupboard -I went, and found this piece, also this stock, in a hat-box; he said he had sold the claret cloth to a servant in Regent-street - we went there, but it was then made into a coat.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>The prisoner begged for mercy, and received a good character.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18310908-291-verdict1499" type="verdictDescription">
